# No obvious workflow nags

The user runs the app and knows how to develop. Do **not** end responses with patronizing reminders about steps they will take on their own.

## Skip by default

- Refresh / hard refresh the page
- Restart the dev server
- Clear browser cache
- Rebuild / re-run after code changes
- "Try placing again" / "open the editor and test"
- Any variant of "you may need to reload to see changes"

## When it is OK to mention a step

Only when it is **non-obvious** and **required** for the fix to take effect — something they would not infer from normal dev workflow:

- A one-time migration that runs only on cold start and is not triggered by HMR
- A cache or version key in code that survives reload until a specific code change lands (say **what changed in code**, not "refresh to pick it up")
- A documented manual step outside the usual edit-save-reload loop (env var, CLI bake, worker restart because the process is separate from the page)

## Review bar

- Would a competent dev already do this without being told? → Delete the sentence.
- Am I explaining **why the bug happened** or nagging **what to click**? → Keep the former, drop the latter.
